hy+%22primary+source%22+%22secondary+source%22&amp;as_brr=3&amp;sig=x4m-T2havCkpLwBPOnQdE0Komkg</a></span></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Seismicity+of+Egypt%2C+Arabia%2C+and+the+Red+Sea&amp;rft.aulast=Ambraseys&amp;rft.aufirst=Nicholas&amp;rft.au=Ambraseys%2C+Nicholas&amp;rft.au=Melville%2C+Charles+Peter&amp;rft.au=Adams%2C+Robin+Dartrey&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B7&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0521391202&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DdtVqdSKnBq4C%26pg%3DPA7%26dq%3Dhistoriography%2B%2522primary%2Bsource%2522%2B%2522secondary%2Bsource%2522%26as_brr%3D3%26sig%3Dx4m-T2havCkpLwBPOnQdE0Komkg&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Primary_source"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> ("The same chronicle can be a primary source for the period contemporary with the author, a secondary source for earlier material derived from previous works, but also a primary source when these earlier works have not survived.").</li>
